"""
mkt-original | 2 Samuel | chapters 8–11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-2samuel-8-11.py

Key translation decisions: chesed (steadfast loyalty/covenant love) dominant in ch9-10;
David's victory list in ch8 uses standard ANE triumph catalog vocabulary;
Lo-debar etymology (place of no pasture/no word); mishpat u-tzedaqah (justice and equity)
at 8:15; dead dog (kelev met) self-deprecation formula; Uriah's loyalty speech and the
irony of the loyal soldier; the narrator's distanced technique in ch11;
the verdict formula me-et YHWH (evil in the eyes of the LORD) at 11:27.

Verses already present: ch8:v15; ch9:v7; ch10:v12; ch11:vv2,15
merge_comm skips them.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}


def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html
    return existing


SAMUEL2 = {
    "8": {
        "1": "<p><em>Vayehi acharei-chen vayak David et-Pelishtim vayakhnieim</em> (&ldquo;after this David struck the Philistines and subdued them&rdquo;). The formula <em>acharei-chen</em> (after this/these things) is the standard transition phrase introducing a new campaign narrative (cf. 2 Sam 10:1; 13:1). The verb <em>nakah</em> (struck down) paired with <em>kana&rsquo;</em> (hiphil: subdued/humbled) is the typical Deuteronomistic victory vocabulary. <em>Metheg-ammah</em> is a hapax of uncertain identification; the parallel in 1 Chr 18:1 reads &ldquo;Gath and its surrounding towns,&rdquo; suggesting this was a key Philistine center. The chapter serves as a summary of David&rsquo;s military reach at the peak of his power.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The Moabite subjugation: David made them lie on the ground and measured with a cord (<em>veyemaddem bacchevel</em>), killing two lengths and sparing one full length. This measuring-for-death is unique in the Hebrew Bible &mdash; no other passage describes exactly this procedure. The Moabite tribute (<em>lamas nose&rsquo; minchah</em>, bearing tribute) uses the standard ANE tribute formulas. The severity toward Moab is unexplained in the text (Ruth was a Moabite; David stored his parents there, 1 Sam 22:3-4). The narrative simply records the conquest without commentary, as is characteristic of the victory catalog genre.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Hadadezer (<em>Hadad-ezer</em>, &ldquo;Hadad is a help&rdquo;) son of Rehob, king of Zobah &mdash; the Aramean kingdom north of Damascus. David struck him down <em>belokho lehashiv yado be-nahar Perath</em> (&ldquo;as Hadadezer was on his way to reassert his control at the Euphrates&rdquo;). The verb <em>hashiv yadо</em> (restore/reassert his hand) implies Hadadezer was attempting to reextend his northern sphere of influence. The Euphrates boundary marks the theoretical extent of Israel&rsquo;s covenanted territory (Gen 15:18; Deut 1:7; 1 Kgs 4:21) &mdash; David&rsquo;s campaign fulfills the Abrahamic territorial promise.</p>",
        "4": "<p>David captured from Hadadezer 1,700 horsemen (<em>parashim</em>) and 20,000 foot soldiers (<em>ragli</em>). He hamstrung (<em>vayeaqer</em>) all the chariot horses (<em>rekhev</em>) except enough for 100 chariots (<em>mea-rekhev hissir lo</em>). <em>Aqar</em> (hamstring, piel) was the prescribed treatment for captured chariot horses in Deut 17:16 and Josh 11:6, 9 &mdash; the Mosaic king legislation prohibited accumulation of horses, a symbol of military self-reliance. Retaining enough for 100 chariots while destroying the rest shows David maintaining the Mosaic constraint even while conducting imperial expansion. 1 Chr 18:4 records 7,000 horsemen &mdash; a textual variant.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The Syrians of Damascus (<em>Aram Dammeseq</em>) came to help Hadadezer; David struck down 22,000 of them. Damascus is mentioned here for the first time in the David narrative. The rescue coalition fails: David defeats the coalition members separately (cf. the Ammonite-Aramean coalition in ch. 10). The number 22,000 is a large round number characteristic of victory tallies in the ANE; such figures function rhetorically to communicate overwhelming victory rather than as precise census counts.</p>",
        "6": "<p>David placed garrisons (<em>nitzavim</em>, from <em>natzav</em>, stand/station) in Aramean Damascus, and the Syrians became vassal-tributaries (<em>vayehi Aram David la-avadim nose&rsquo;ei minchah</em>, &ldquo;and Aram became David&rsquo;s servants bearing tribute&rdquo;). The repeated refrain: <em>vayoshea YHWH et-David bekhol asher halakh</em> (&ldquo;the LORD preserved/saved David wherever he went&rdquo;). This divine-preservation formula appears twice (vv. 6, 14) as a bracket around the campaign summary, interpreting all of David&rsquo;s military success as YHWH&rsquo;s work rather than David&rsquo;s military skill.</p>",
        "7": "<p>David took the gold shields (<em>shiltei ha-zahav</em>) carried by Hadadezer&rsquo;s officers and brought them to Jerusalem. <em>Shelet</em> (shield/quiver, also rendered &ldquo;shield cases&rdquo;) appears in the NT era as a loan-word in Greek; the gold shields are trophies of victory dedicated to YHWH rather than retained as personal wealth. The pattern of dedicating military plunder to YHWH&rsquo;s treasury is the same as Samuel&rsquo;s demand that Agag be devoted and the Amalekite cattle consecrated (1 Sam 15:3) &mdash; the principle of <em>cherem</em> (devotion to YHWH) applied to foreign wealth.</p>",
        "8": "<p>From Betah (<em>Tebah</em> in 1 Chr 18:8) and Berothai, cities of Hadadezer, David took a very large quantity of bronze (<em>nechashet harbeh me&rsquo;od</em>). Bronze was the primary metal for weapons and construction in this period before iron technology became dominant. Solomon will use this bronze for the temple furnishings (1 Kgs 7:13-47; cf. 1 Chr 18:8 explicitly connects this bronze to the temple). David&rsquo;s wars thus provision the temple David is not permitted to build &mdash; a transfer of war-spoil into sacred architecture mediated by a generation.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Toi (<em>Tou</em> in 1 Chr 18:9), king of Hamath, heard that David had destroyed the whole army of Hadadezer (<em>hikah David et kol tzeva Hadad-ezer</em>). Hamath was a significant Aramean city-state on the Orontes River, north of Zobah. Since Hadadezer had been Toi&rsquo;s enemy (<em>ki ish milchamot Tou hayah Hadad-ezer</em>), David&rsquo;s victory serves Hamath&rsquo;s interests. The political intelligence Toi demonstrates &mdash; recognizing the new dominant power and sending an immediate diplomatic mission &mdash; is the standard response of smaller kingdoms to rising empires throughout the ANE.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Toi sent his son Joram (<em>Yehoram</em> in 1 Chr 18:10, a theophoric form) to David to extend greetings and congratulate him (<em>leshalem lo ulevarkho</em>, &ldquo;to greet him and bless him&rdquo;). <em>Shalem</em> (piel: establish peace, complete a formal greeting) is the root of <em>shalom</em>. Joram brought vessels of silver, gold, and bronze (<em>keli keseph u-khle zahav u-khle nechoshet</em>) &mdash; the standard diplomatic gift categories. The name Joram (&ldquo;YHWH is exalted&rdquo;) is ironic for a son of a Aramean king who worships Hadad; it may reflect the family&rsquo;s political accommodation to Israelite power.</p>",
        "11": "<p>David dedicated these (<em>gam otam hiqdish ha-melekh David laYHWH</em>) to YHWH along with all the silver and gold he had set apart (<em>hivdil</em>) from the nations he had conquered. The verb <em>hiqdish</em> (consecrate/dedicate, hiphil of <em>qadash</em>) converts military booty into sacred donation. The verb <em>hivdil</em> (separate out) is used for the priestly act of distinguishing holy from common (Lev 10:10). David&rsquo;s military treasury is systematically transferred to YHWH&rsquo;s domain &mdash; the spoils of empire become the endowment for the temple.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The enumeration of conquered nations: Edom, Moab, Ammon, Philistines, Amalek, and the plunder from Hadadezer. Six nations/peoples appear in this tribute catalog. The list partially fulfills the enemies specified in YHWH&rsquo;s commission to Israel (Deut 7:1: the seven nations; the Amalekites as special enemies, Exod 17:16; Deut 25:17-19). Amalek is mentioned last &mdash; the perpetual enemy whose subjugation was commanded before the monarchy began (1 Sam 15). The completeness of the list signals the fulfillment of covenantal promises.</p>",
        "13": "<p>David made a name (<em>vaya&rsquo;as David shem</em>) when he returned from killing Edomites in the Valley of Salt (<em>Gei ha-Melach</em>). <em>Shem</em> (name, reputation) is the reward of great deeds. The Valley of Salt is identified with a saltflat south of the Dead Sea. The number 18,000 Edomites killed is a round figure; 1 Chr 18:12 attributes the victory to Abishai and records the same number. The discrepancy may reflect different aspects of the same campaign or a scribal harmonization issue. What matters theologically is the subjugation of Edom (descendant of Esau), fulfilling the oracle of Gen 25:23.</p>",
        "14": "<p>Garrisons throughout Edom (<em>vayasem be-Edom nitzavim bekhol Edom</em>) and all Edomites became David&rsquo;s subjects (<em>vayehi khol-Edom avadim leDavid</em>). The repetition of the formula <em>vayoshea YHWH et-David bekhol asher halakh</em> (&ldquo;the LORD preserved David wherever he went&rdquo;) closes the victory catalog as it opened it (v. 6). The structural bracket is interpretive: the conquest is YHWH&rsquo;s work, not David&rsquo;s military genius. The fulfilled oracle of Gen 27:40 (Esau will serve Jacob) is the covenantal framework for the Edom subjugation.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The administrative list (<em>reshimat ha-paqqidim</em>): Joab (<em>Yo&rsquo;av</em>) son of Zeruiah over the army (<em>al-ha-tzava</em>); Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud as recorder (<em>mazkir</em>). The <em>mazkir</em> (one who records/brings to memory) was a high court official in Egyptian and Israelite administration, possibly the official responsible for presenting reports and recording royal decisions. The list follows the pattern of Egyptian and Mesopotamian administrative rosters that accompanied victory catalogs. A similar list appears in 2 Sam 20:23-26, reflecting an expanded administration later in David&rsquo;s reign.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Zadok (<em>Tzadoq</em>) son of Ahitub and Ahimelech son of Abiathar as priests (<em>kohanim</em>). The dual-priest arrangement is significant: Zadok is an Aaronide from the line that will eventually displace Abiathar&rsquo;s Elide line (1 Kgs 2:26-27). Seraiah (<em>Seraya</em>) as secretary (<em>sofer</em>). The <em>sofer</em> (scribe/secretary) was a key administrative official responsible for correspondence and legal documents (cf. 2 Kgs 12:10; 18:18). The list of officials mirrors known ANE palace administrative structures.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Benaiah (<em>Benayahu</em>) son of Jehoiada over the Cherethites and Pelethites (<em>ha-Keretî ve-ha-Peletî</em>). The Cherethites (possibly Cretans or Philistines) and Pelethites were David&rsquo;s elite mercenary bodyguard &mdash; non-Israelite professional soldiers loyal to the king personally rather than to tribal or national interests. Their presence in David&rsquo;s court reflects the cosmopolitan nature of his administration. <em>Uvnei David kohanim hayu</em> (&ldquo;and David&rsquo;s sons served as royal priests&rdquo;). The priestly function of the king&rsquo;s sons is unusual; 1 Chr 18:17 replaces <em>kohanim</em> with <em>rishonim le-yad ha-melekh</em> (chief officials at the king&rsquo;s side), perhaps softening the priestly implication.</p>",
    },
    "9": {
        "1": "<p><em>Vayomer David ha-yesh od asher notar le-veit Sha&rsquo;ul ve-e&rsquo;eseh imo chesed ba-avur Yehonatan</em> (&ldquo;Is there anyone still left from the house of Saul to whom I can show steadfast loyalty for Jonathan&rsquo;s sake?&rdquo;). The word <em>chesed</em> (covenant loyalty, steadfast love, kindness) is the operative term of the entire chapter and appears in vv. 1, 3, and 7. <em>Chesed</em> is the relational word at the heart of covenant theology: YHWH&rsquo;s covenant loyalty toward Israel and the human analog to that loyalty between covenant partners. The <em>chesed</em> David seeks to enact toward Saul&rsquo;s house is grounded in his covenant with Jonathan (1 Sam 18:3; 20:12-17; 23:18).</p>",
        "2": "<p>A servant of Saul&rsquo;s household named Ziba (<em>eved le-veit Sha&rsquo;ul ushmo Tziva</em>). They summoned (<em>vayiqre&rsquo;u</em>) him to David; the king asked if he was Ziba. His response: <em>avdekha</em> (&ldquo;your servant&rdquo;) rather than <em>ani</em> (&ldquo;I&rdquo;) &mdash; the standard form of address to a superior. The name Ziba appears without etymology but will become theologically significant when his loyalty to David is tested and ultimately found ambiguous in the Absalom crisis (2 Sam 16:1-4; 19:24-30). His introduction here as a loyal servant sets up a later irony.</p>",
        "3": "<p><em>Ha-yesh od ish le-veit Sha&rsquo;ul ve-e&rsquo;eseh imo chesed elohim</em> (&ldquo;Is there no one left of the house of Saul to whom I can show the loyal love of God?&rdquo;). The phrase <em>chesed elohim</em> (the loyal love of God, or: divine-quality chesed) intensifies the earlier <em>chesed</em>: what David seeks to do is modeled on, and participates in, YHWH&rsquo;s own chesed. Ziba&rsquo;s report: <em>yesh le-Yehonatan ben nekheh raglayim</em> (&ldquo;Jonathan still has a son who is lame in both feet&rdquo;). The disability is mentioned immediately &mdash; Mephibosheth&rsquo;s lameness is part of his identity throughout (9:13; 2 Sam 4:4; 19:26). He became lame when dropped by his nurse fleeing after the Jezreel battle (2 Sam 4:4).</p>",
        "4": "<p>Mephibosheth (<em>Mephiboshet</em>, possibly a deliberate distortion of <em>Meribba&rsquo;al</em> to avoid the Baal component; see 1 Chr 8:34; 9:40) is at the house of Machir (<em>Makhir</em>) son of Ammiel in Lo-debar. <em>Lo-debar</em> (or <em>Lidbir</em>) may mean &ldquo;no pasture&rdquo; or &ldquo;without word&rdquo; (<em>lo + davar/diber</em>). The name suggests marginality &mdash; a place off the main routes, appropriate for a political refugee from the previous dynasty. Machir appears later as one of David&rsquo;s supporters who provided supplies during the Absalom crisis (2 Sam 17:27-29), establishing him as a wealthy loyalist in Transjordan.</p>",
        "5": "<p>David sent and brought Mephibosheth from the house of Machir in Lo-debar. The sending-and-bringing formula (<em>vayishlach ha-melekh David vayiqachehu</em>) is a royal summons. The journey from Lo-debar (east of Jordan, in Gilead) to Jerusalem involved crossing the Jordan and ascending to the city. For a lame man whose grandfather&rsquo;s dynasty had been displaced by the man summoning him, the summons carried obvious peril. Mephibosheth would have had reason to fear a political execution cloaked in invitation.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Mephibosheth came and prostrated himself (<em>vayipol al-panav vayishtachu</em>). David called him: <em>Mephiboshet</em> &mdash; his full name. Mephibosheth replied: <em>hinneh avdekha</em> (&ldquo;here is your servant&rdquo;). The same <em>hinneni</em>/<em>hinneh avdekha</em> formula as Samuel&rsquo;s response to the divine call (1 Sam 3:4-6). Mephibosheth uses the self-designation <em>avdekha</em> (your servant) throughout his speech &mdash; the posture of total submission to royal authority. His prostration echoes the posture of the conquered foreign kings in the victory catalog, but this is a covenant act of grace rather than military submission.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Mephibosheth&rsquo;s self-deprecation: <em>mah avdekha ki phanaita el ha-kelev ha-met asher kamoni</em> (&ldquo;what is your servant, that you should give attention to a dead dog like me?&rdquo;). The <em>kelev met</em> (dead dog) formula is the strongest self-humiliation expression in the Hebrew Bible. In the ancient Near East, dogs were scavengers, and to call oneself a dead dog is to claim the lowest possible social status. Mephibosheth uses the formula that Abigail used to David (1 Sam 25:41: servant who washes feet) and that Ziba will echo (9:9). The dead-dog formula appears when a lesser person is overwhelmed by unexpected royal favor.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The king summoned Ziba and transferred management of Saul&rsquo;s estate to Mephibosheth: <em>kol asher hayah le-Sha&rsquo;ul ul-khol-beito natatti levn adonikhah</em> (&ldquo;I have given to your master&rsquo;s grandson everything that belonged to Saul and his family&rdquo;). The restoration of land confiscated from a defeated dynasty is unusual in the ANE; typically such land was redistributed to the conqueror&rsquo;s supporters. David&rsquo;s restoration of Saul&rsquo;s estate to his heir enacts the <em>chesed elohim</em> he announced (v. 3) &mdash; a counter-ANE act of covenantal loyalty.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Ziba, his fifteen sons, and twenty servants are to farm the land and bring in the produce (<em>ve-avadtem lo et-ha-adamah</em>) for Mephibosheth&rsquo;s household. <em>Mephiboshet ben-adonikhah yokhal lechem al-shulchani tamid</em> (&ldquo;but Mephibosheth himself shall always eat at my table&rdquo;). The repeated phrase &ldquo;eat at my table&rdquo; (vv. 7, 10, 11, 13) becomes the chapter&rsquo;s keynote: table-fellowship as the expression of restored covenant status. The king&rsquo;s table is a place of honor and security (cf. Ps 23:5: &ldquo;you prepare a table before me in the presence of my enemies&rdquo;). Mephibosheth eating at David&rsquo;s table as a son of the house is an act of political incorporation into the royal family.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Ziba&rsquo;s compliance: <em>ke-khol asher yetzavveh adoni ha-melekh et avdo ken ya&rsquo;aseh avdekha</em> (&ldquo;your servant will do everything my lord the king commands&rdquo;). The verse concludes: <em>veMephiboshet yokhel al-shulchan David kachad mibenei ha-melekh</em> (&ldquo;so Mephibosheth ate at David&rsquo;s table, like one of the king&rsquo;s sons&rdquo;). The simile <em>ke-achad mibenei ha-melekh</em> (like one of the king&rsquo;s sons) is the highest status language: the lame son of the displaced dynasty is treated with royal-family honor. This is a type of what the NT calls adoption: those outside the royal household brought in as sons through an act of undeserved grace (<em>chesed</em>).</p>",
        "12": "<p>Mephibosheth had a young son named Micha (<em>Mikha&rsquo;</em>). All who lived in Ziba&rsquo;s household became servants to Mephibosheth. The mention of Micha extends the covenant: David&rsquo;s <em>chesed</em> toward Jonathan (through Mephibosheth) is now extended one more generation &mdash; the grandson of Jonathan will grow up in Ziba&rsquo;s household supported by David&rsquo;s covenant provision. The narrative thus shows <em>chesed</em> operating across three generations: Jonathan&rsquo;s covenant (generation 1) → Mephibosheth&rsquo;s restoration (generation 2) → Micha&rsquo;s inheritance (generation 3).</p>",
        "13": "<p>Mephibosheth lived in Jerusalem, eating regularly at the king&rsquo;s table (<em>veMephiboshet yoshev biYrushalayim ki al-shulchan ha-melekh tamid hu yokhel</em>). The closing notation &mdash; <em>vehu pisequach shtei raglav</em> (&ldquo;he was lame in both feet&rdquo;) &mdash; returns to the detail first mentioned in v. 3, framing the chapter: the lame man who had every reason to fear the king now lives at the king&rsquo;s table. The disability is not healed; it remains as a permanent visible marker of where Mephibosheth came from. His welcome is entirely a function of covenant loyalty, not his own capability or standing.</p>",
    },
    "10": {
        "1": "<p><em>Vayehi acharei-chen vayamot melekh benei Ammon vayimlokh Chanun beno tachtav</em> (&ldquo;some time later the king of the Ammonites died, and his son Hanun succeeded him&rdquo;). The formula <em>acharei-chen</em> links this to the previous narrative. The Ammonite king&rsquo;s death creates a diplomatic opportunity: the transition between rulers is the standard occasion for affirming or renegotiating treaties. David&rsquo;s initiative to send consolation to Hanun is consistent with the <em>chesed</em> theme of ch. 9 &mdash; David extends covenant loyalty (<em>chesed</em>) to Nahash&rsquo;s son as Nahash had apparently shown loyalty to David (the nature of that earlier <em>chesed</em> is unexplained).</p>",
        "2": "<p>David&rsquo;s stated motive: <em>a&rsquo;eseh chesed im-Chanun ben-Nachash ka-asher asah aviv itti chesed</em> (&ldquo;I will show steadfast loyalty to Hanun... as his father showed loyalty to me&rdquo;). The <em>chesed</em>-reciprocity principle: David&rsquo;s loyal love is grounded in received loyal love. This is the covenantal principle of Exod 34:6-7 applied horizontally: the one who has received chesed extends chesed. David sends his servants (<em>avadav</em>) to express condolences (<em>lenachemо</em>, from <em>nachem</em>, comfort/console &mdash; the same verb as for YHWH comforting his people in Isa 40:1) over the death of Hanun&rsquo;s father.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The Ammonite commanders (<em>sarei benei Ammon</em>) suspected David&rsquo;s motives: <em>hamkhabbeid David et-avikhah be-einekha ki shalach lekha menachamim ha-lo bishevil chaqor et-ha-ir ulegargalah ul-haphkho shalach David et-avadav eilekha</em> (&ldquo;Do you really think David is honoring your father... Has David not sent his servants to search the city, spy it out, and overthrow it?&rdquo;). The three-part accusation uses military intelligence vocabulary: <em>chaqar</em> (search/investigate), <em>gargal</em> (spy out/reconnoiter), and <em>haphakh</em> (overthrow). Diplomatic missions were sometimes used for intelligence gathering (cf. Josh 2: the spies at Jericho). The Ammonite suspicion is historically plausible even if wrong in this case.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Hanun&rsquo;s insult: he seized David&rsquo;s servants, shaved half of each man&rsquo;s beard (<em>vayegallach et-chatzi zeqanam</em>), cut their garments in half at the waist (<em>vayikhrot et-madeihem bachatzî ad-shethotehem</em>), and sent them away. Both actions are calculated humiliations: in the ancient Near East, the beard was a marker of male dignity and honor, and shaving it was a form of degradation (cf. Isa 50:6; Ezra 9:3). Cutting the garments to expose the buttocks (<em>shethotehem</em>) was a form of sexual humiliation. These acts constitute an act of war since David&rsquo;s envoys represented his person.</p>",
        "5": "<p>David was told and sent men to meet the returning envoys, for they were deeply shamed (<em>ki hayu ha-anashim niklamin me&rsquo;od</em>). The verb <em>kalam</em> (niphal: be put to shame, humiliated) expresses social dishonor. David&rsquo;s instruction: stay at Jericho (<em>shvu be-Yericho</em>) until your beards have grown back, then return. Jericho was a frontier city where the shamed men could wait privately rather than walking through Jerusalem in their humiliated state. The act of waiting for beard regrowth is a rehabilitation of their public dignity before return &mdash; David protects his servants&rsquo; honor as he expects their honor to have been protected.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The Ammonites realized they had become a stench (<em>vayar&rsquo;u benei Ammon ki nib&rsquo;ashu beDavid</em>, literally &ldquo;they had become stinking to David&rdquo;, a Hebraism for making themselves repugnant/offensive). They hired mercenaries: the Syrians of Beth-rehob and Zobah (20,000 foot soldiers), plus the king of Maacah (1,000 men), plus the men of Tob (12,000 men). The Ammonites compensate for their weakness by purchasing a coalition. The irony: David&rsquo;s act of <em>chesed</em> now requires military response, and the misreading of <em>chesed</em> as espionage triggers a war that eventually leads to Uriah&rsquo;s death and David&rsquo;s great sin (ch. 11).</p>",
        "7": "<p>David sent Joab and all Israel, including the mighty men (<em>kol ha-tzava ha-gibborim</em>). The <em>gibborim</em> (mighty men) are David&rsquo;s elite warriors cataloged in 2 Sam 23:8-39. The word <em>gibbor</em> (mighty/warrior) is the term for Goliath (1 Sam 17:51) and for the heroic fighters of David&rsquo;s inner circle. The full mobilization of Israel plus the elite corps indicates David takes the combined Ammonite-Aramean coalition seriously.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Battle formation: the Ammonites at the entrance of the city gate (<em>petach ha-sha&rsquo;ar</em>), while the Syrians took position in the open country (<em>bassadeh levad</em>). This pincer formation &mdash; city forces at the gate behind Joab, coalition forces in the open field around him &mdash; is a classic ancient encirclement tactic. The narration of the battle positions is given in precise military terms before describing Joab&rsquo;s tactical response.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Joab saw that the battle lines were set against him both in front and behind (<em>ki hayetah panav ha-milchamah el-panav ve-el-achor</em>) and selected the best troops of Israel (<em>vayivchar mikol bechurai be-Yisra&rsquo;el</em>) to deploy against the Syrians. The tactical problem &mdash; a two-front threat &mdash; requires dividing the force. Joab takes the more dangerous Syrian contingent (the paid professionals) himself and assigns his brother Abishai to the Ammonite front. Military command decisions in Hebrew narrative are rendered efficiently: the plan is stated, not deliberated.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The remaining troops placed under Abishai (<em>Avishai achihu</em>) and deployed against the Ammonites. The brothers&rsquo; mutual support arrangement reflects both the tactical and the familial nature of David&rsquo;s command structure &mdash; Joab and Abishai are sons of Zeruiah, David&rsquo;s sister. The Zeruiah clan plays a disproportionate role in David&rsquo;s military, for good and ill (Joab will become a problem in the succession narrative).</p>",
        "11": "<p>Joab&rsquo;s instructions to Abishai: if the Syrians are too strong (<em>im-techezeq mimmeni ha-Aram</em>), Abishai must help; if the Ammonites are too strong (<em>im-yechezeq mimenekha ben-Ammon</em>), Joab will help. The conditional mutual-support agreement is a practical battlefield covenant. The word <em>chazaq</em> (be/become strong) is the standard military strength verb (also the commissioning word of Josh 1:6-9). The brothers enter battle with a clear plan for dealing with either front becoming overwhelming.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Joab and his men advanced (<em>vayiggash Yo&rsquo;av ve-ha-am asher ito la-milchamah bi-Aram</em>) against the Syrians, and the Syrians fled (<em>vayanusu mipanav</em>). The battle narrative is characteristically brief: the advance, the flight of the enemy, and the flight of the Ammonites when they saw the Syrian rout. The compression (vv. 13-14) contrasts with the narrative expansion of the campaign preparations (vv. 6-12). The battle itself is less important than the strategic and moral context around it.</p>",
        "14": "<p>When the Ammonites saw that the Syrians fled (<em>vayir&rsquo;u benei Ammon ki nas Aram</em>), they fled before Abishai (<em>mipnei Avishai</em>) and entered the city. Joab turned back (<em>vayashov Yo&rsquo;av</em>) from the Ammonites and came to Jerusalem. The first campaign ends without a decisive siege of Rabbah &mdash; that will come in ch. 11-12. Joab&rsquo;s withdrawal preserves forces for the second campaign while the Ammonites regroup.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The Syrians, seeing they had been routed (<em>ki nugephu lifnei Yisra&rsquo;el</em>), regrouped (<em>vayeassephu yachdav</em>). The regrouping of the defeated coalition mirrors the Philistine recovery after various defeats in the judges period. Military defeat rarely ends a conflict permanently; the pursuit of renewed advantage requires a new coalition. The Syrians will bring in reserves from beyond the Euphrates (v. 16) to compensate for their local defeat.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Hadadezer sent (<em>vayishlach Hadad-ezer</em>) and brought out the Syrians from beyond the Euphrates River (<em>me&rsquo;ever ha-nahar</em>), and they came to Helam with Shobach the commander of Hadadezer&rsquo;s army (<em>Shovakh sar-tzeva Hadad-ezer lifneihem</em>). The reinforcements from Trans-Euphrates represents a significant escalation: the first Syrian campaign (ch. 8) was against Hadadezer&rsquo;s local forces; now his broader empire is engaged. Helam is unidentified but appears to be a Trans-Jordanian site.</p>",
        "17": "<p>David mustered all Israel (<em>vayeasphu et-kol Yisra&rsquo;el</em>), crossed the Jordan, and arrived at Helam. The king himself leads this campaign, unlike the first Ammonite campaign where Joab commanded. The personal royal leadership of a decisive battle is the highest military commitment. The Syrians formed battle lines (<em>vaya&rsquo;arkhu litqrat David vayillachamu imo</em>) against David and attacked &mdash; the battle is framed as personal challenge to the king.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The Syrians fled before Israel (<em>vayanos Aram mipnei Yisra&rsquo;el</em>). David struck down 700 chariot crews (<em>sheva-me&rsquo;ot rekhev</em>) and 40,000 horsemen (<em>arba&rsquo;im elef parash</em>), and killed Shobach the army commander. The 1 Chr 19:18 parallel records 7,000 chariot crews and 40,000 foot soldiers &mdash; textual variants likely reflecting different transmission of the large numbers. Shobach&rsquo;s death (<em>vayamot sham</em>) removes the enemy commander and marks a decisive victory.</p>",
        "19": "<p>All the kings who served under Hadadezer saw they had been defeated by Israel (<em>ki nugephu lifnei Yisra&rsquo;el</em>) and made peace with Israel (<em>vayashlemu im Yisra&rsquo;el vaya&rsquo;avdum</em>) and submitted to them. <em>Vayira Aram le-hosea&rsquo; od et-benei Ammon</em> (&ldquo;after that, the Syrians were afraid to help the Ammonites any further&rdquo;). The strategic outcome: the Ammonite coalition is permanently broken, leaving Ammon isolated. The stage is set for the final campaign against Rabbah in ch. 11 &mdash; a campaign David will direct from Jerusalem while Joab conducts the siege, with disastrous moral consequences.</p>",
    },
    "11": {
        "1": "<p><em>Vayehi litshuvat ha-shanah le-et tzeit ha-melakhim</em> (&ldquo;in the spring, when kings typically march out to war&rdquo;). The phrase <em>teshuvat ha-shanah</em> (the turning/return of the year) is the spring agricultural-military season when roads were dry and campaigns were feasible. The convention <em>le-et tzeit ha-melakhim</em> (the time kings go out) identifies this as the normal season for royal military leadership. David sends Joab with the fighting forces &mdash; but <em>David yashuv biYrushalayim</em> (&ldquo;David himself stayed in Jerusalem&rdquo;). The narrative&rsquo;s first word of moral evaluation is structural: the king who should be at war is instead at home. The Ammonite war has been ongoing; the choice to remain is David&rsquo;s decision, not necessity.</p>",
        "3": "<p>David sent someone to investigate and was told: <em>halo-zot Bat-Sheva bat-Eliam eshet Uriyah ha-Chitti</em> (&ldquo;she is Bathsheba daughter of Eliam, the wife of Uriah the Hittite&rdquo;). The three-part identification is progressively clarifying and progressively damning: her name (Bathsheba), her father&rsquo;s name (Eliam, one of David&rsquo;s thirty mighty men per 2 Sam 23:34), and her marital status (wife of Uriah the Hittite &mdash; another of David&rsquo;s thirty mighty men, 2 Sam 23:39). David is told clearly who she is. The information names her married status before anything else; the inquiry has produced the one fact that should stop the king.</p>",
        "4": "<p><em>Vayishlach David mal&rsquo;akhim vayiqqachenah</em> (&ldquo;David sent messengers to bring her&rdquo;). The repeated verb <em>shalach</em> (send) has been the word of David&rsquo;s royal action throughout the chapter: he sends Joab (v. 1), sends someone to inquire (v. 3), sends messengers for Bathsheba (v. 4), sends for Uriah (v. 6). The sending that expressed <em>chesed</em> in ch. 9-10 has become the sending of exploitation. She came, he lay with her (<em>vatavo elav vayishkav immah</em>). The notation <em>vehi mitqaddesheth mitum&rsquo;atah</em> (&ldquo;she had just completed her ritual purification from her monthly uncleanness&rdquo;) &mdash; confirming she is not already pregnant; the resulting pregnancy is David&rsquo;s.</p>",
        "5": "<p><em>Vathar ha-ishshah vatishtlach vattagged leDavid vatomer harah anokhi</em> (&ldquo;the woman became pregnant, and she sent word to David: &lsquo;I am pregnant.&rsquo;&rdquo;). The terseness of the message &mdash; three Hebrew words (<em>harah anokhi</em>, &ldquo;pregnant I am&rdquo;) plus the verb &mdash; is the most economical sentence of crisis in the entire chapter. Bathsheba does not plead, demand, or accuse. She simply reports. The implication of the report is everything: the king must act. The narrative does not give Bathsheba&rsquo;s interior state; her agency is limited to this three-word communication.</p>",
        "6": "<p>David sent to Joab: <em>shalach eilai et-Uriyah ha-Chitti</em> (&ldquo;Send me Uriah the Hittite&rdquo;). So Joab sent Uriah to David. The cover-up plan begins. Uriah&rsquo;s name means &ldquo;YHWH is my light&rdquo; &mdash; the faithful soldier with the theophoric name will be manipulated and ultimately murdered by the king whose covenant loyalty was the theme of the preceding chapters. Uriah the Hittite is a non-Israelite serving in Israel&rsquo;s army with greater covenant fidelity than Israel&rsquo;s king will demonstrate.</p>",
        "7": "<p>When Uriah arrived, David asked about Joab&rsquo;s welfare (<em>bishalom Yo&rsquo;av</em>), the troops&rsquo; welfare (<em>bishlom ha-am</em>), and the war&rsquo;s progress (<em>bishlom ha-milchamah</em>). The triple <em>shalom</em> inquiry is a standard greeting ritual but also a cover for the real purpose of the meeting. David is performing normalcy &mdash; as if calling a trusted soldier in for a campaign briefing. The word <em>shalom</em> that echoes through these verses will be notably absent from what follows.</p>",
        "8": "<p>David&rsquo;s instruction: <em>red le-veitekha urchatz raglekha</em> (&ldquo;go home and rest&rdquo;, literally &ldquo;go down to your house and wash your feet&rdquo;). Washing feet was the first act after returning from a journey. David sent a gift (<em>mas&rsquo;et ha-melekh</em>, a royal present) after him &mdash; a bribe intended to encourage domestic ease. The foot-washing invitation is euphemistic for returning to conjugal relations with his wife; the gift is an additional inducement. Both are attempts to create the paternity fiction without Uriah&rsquo;s knowledge.</p>",
        "9": "<p>But Uriah slept at the entrance of the palace with all the king&rsquo;s other servants (<em>vayishkav Uriyah petach beit ha-melekh im kol-avdei adonav</em>). He did not go home. The refusal is unexplained &mdash; did Uriah suspect? Was he simply observing campaign protocol? The narrative leaves it ambiguous. The word <em>velo yared el-beito</em> (&ldquo;he did not go home&rdquo;) is the hinge on which the cover-up plan fails. Uriah&rsquo;s military fidelity will prove unbreakable through direct instruction (v. 11), through drunkenness (v. 13), and ultimately through death.</p>",
        "10": "<p>David, informed of Uriah&rsquo;s refusal, asked: <em>halo min-ha-derekh atah ba madua lo yeradta el-beitekha</em> (&ldquo;you have just come back from a long journey &mdash; why did you not go home?&rdquo;). The question is disingenuous; David knows exactly why he wants Uriah to go home. The phrase <em>min-ha-derekh atah ba</em> (you have come from the road/journey) is both a factual acknowledgment and an invitation: after the journey, the natural thing is domestic rest.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Uriah&rsquo;s answer is the moral center of the chapter: <em>ha-aron ve-Yisra&rsquo;el veYehudah yoshevim ba-sukkot va-adoni Yo&rsquo;av ve-avdei adoni al-penei ha-sadeh chonin va-ani avo el-beiti le-ekhol veli-shtot ule-shkhav im-ishti chayyekha vekhay napshekha im-e&rsquo;eseh et ha-davar hazeh</em> (&ldquo;the ark and Israel and Judah are staying in tents, and my lord Joab and your servants are camped in the open country. Should I then go home to eat and drink and sleep with my wife?&rdquo;). Uriah&rsquo;s refusal is grounded in solidarity with the ark, with Israel, and with his fellow soldiers. The mention of the ark first &mdash; in the field, vulnerable, without the king who should be with it &mdash; is an indirect rebuke of David&rsquo;s absence. The oath formula <em>chayyekha vekhay napshekha</em> (as you live and as your soul lives) is the king&rsquo;s life invoked as the witness to Uriah&rsquo;s vow.</p>",
        "12": "<p>David&rsquo;s response: <em>shev poh gam-ha-yom umachar ashalechekha</em> (&ldquo;stay here today as well, and tomorrow I will let you go&rdquo;). The promise of release tomorrow is false &mdash; David&rsquo;s actual plan is forming. The extra day in Jerusalem is a second opportunity to get Uriah home. Uriah stayed that day and the next in Jerusalem, still not going home. The repetition of his refusal (<em>lo rad el-beito</em>, &ldquo;he did not go home&rdquo;) emphasizes that Uriah is consistently refusing what David offers, not from stubbornness but from principle.</p>",
        "13": "<p>David invited him to eat and drink (<em>vayiqra-lo David vayokhal lefanav vayisht</em>) and made him drunk (<em>vayeshakkerehu</em>). But in the evening Uriah went out to sleep among the king&rsquo;s servants, still not going home. The verb <em>shakhar</em> (make drunk, piel) appears in Gen 43:34 for Benjamin receiving five times as much food &mdash; festive excess. David&rsquo;s drunkenness strategy assumes that inhibitions lowered by wine will overcome Uriah&rsquo;s principled abstention. The strategy fails: drunk or sober, Uriah maintains his soldiers&rsquo; solidarity. The Hittite soldier outperforms the Israelite king in covenant loyalty.</p>",
        "14": "<p>In the morning David wrote a letter to Joab (<em>vayikhtov David sepher el Yo&rsquo;av</em>) and sent it in Uriah&rsquo;s hand (<em>vayishlach beyad Uriyah</em>). The terrible irony is explicit in the Hebrew: the man carries his own death warrant. <em>Sepher</em> (letter/written document) appears rarely in the Hebrew Bible; this is one of the earliest mentions of a written royal letter used for administrative purposes. Uriah&rsquo;s illiteracy &mdash; or his trust in David &mdash; is what makes him the unwitting bearer of the letter that orders his death.</p>",
        "16": "<p>While Joab had the city under siege (<em>vishmor Yo&rsquo;av el-ha-ir</em>), he stationed Uriah at the point where he knew the strongest defenders were (<em>el ha-maqom asher yada&rsquo; ki anshei chayil sham</em>). Joab&rsquo;s execution of the plan is careful: he doesn&rsquo;t simply order Uriah to run at a wall, but places him where experienced soldiers know the defenders are strongest. The exposure looks tactical rather than deliberate. The verb <em>yada&rsquo;</em> (knew) for Joab&rsquo;s tactical knowledge echoes the &ldquo;knowing&rdquo; throughout the chapter: David knew who Bathsheba was (v. 3-4), Joab knows where the danger is (v. 16), YHWH knows what David has done (v. 27).</p>",
        "17": "<p>The city&rsquo;s men sallied out (<em>vayetz&rsquo;u anshe ha-ir vayillachamu et Yo&rsquo;av</em>) and attacked Joab&rsquo;s forces. Some of David&rsquo;s servants fell, and Uriah the Hittite died too (<em>vayamot gam Uriyah ha-Chitti</em>). The placement of <em>gam</em> (also/too) before Uriah&rsquo;s name is striking: he dies alongside other soldiers, making his death look incidental. The cover-up of murder as acceptable military casualty is the final obscenity of the episode. The phrase <em>gam Uriyah ha-Chitti</em> stands out from the narrative like an accusation.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Joab sent a report (<em>vayishlach Yo&rsquo;av vayaggeid leDavid et kol divrei ha-milchamah</em>) to David about the full course of the battle. The messenger is given elaborate instructions for anticipating David&rsquo;s anger at the tactical exposure (vv. 19-21). Joab anticipates that David will be angry at the tactical blunder that cost soldiers their lives. The messenger&rsquo;s instructions to mention Uriah as the final item are a briefing in crisis communication: save the key information for when David&rsquo;s anger is rising, to neutralize it.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Joab&rsquo;s instruction to the messenger: <em>ke-khalotekha et kol divrei ha-milchamah ledabber el-ha-melekh</em> (&ldquo;after you have given the king the full account of the battle&rdquo;). The sequence is deliberate: full battle report first, then Uriah&rsquo;s death. The messenger will need to manage David&rsquo;s emotional response to military failure before delivering the information that transforms military failure into success from David&rsquo;s perspective. The dark comedy of the situation &mdash; Joab coaching his messenger to navigate the king&rsquo;s reactions &mdash; reveals how thoroughly the court has been corrupted.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Joab anticipates David&rsquo;s rebuke: <em>madua niggashtem el ha-ir lahelachem halo yeda&rsquo;atem et asher yorehu me-al ha-chomah</em> (&ldquo;Why did you go so close to the city? Did you not know they would shoot from the wall?&rdquo;). The reference to arrows from the wall is the standard siege-warfare caution: city defenders had the height advantage. David&rsquo;s anticipated criticism is tactically correct and would normally be appropriate military leadership feedback.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Joab references the Abimelech incident: <em>mi-hikkah et Avimelekh ben Yerubbeshet halo-ishah hashlikhah alov peleach rekhayim me-al ha-chomah vayamot beThevetz</em> (&ldquo;Who struck down Abimelech son of Jerubbesheth? Was it not a woman who dropped a millstone on him from the wall at Thebez?&rdquo;). This references Judg 9:50-55. <em>Yerubbeshet</em> (for <em>Yerubba&rsquo;al</em>) follows the pattern of substituting <em>boshet</em> (shame) for <em>ba&rsquo;al</em> in names to avoid the divine epithet. The millstone death at Thebez was a proverbial example of siege-warfare folly. Joab uses this example as the anticipated context for the messenger&rsquo;s final line: &ldquo;then say, Your servant Uriah the Hittite is dead also.&rdquo;</p>",
        "22": "<p>The messenger came and told David everything Joab had sent him to report. The brief report of compliance (<em>vayavo ha-mal&rsquo;akh vayaggeid leDavid et kol asher shalcho Yo&rsquo;av</em>) mirrors the pattern throughout the chapter where instructions are executed without variation. The narrative does not record the messenger deviating from Joab&rsquo;s script &mdash; in the event, the messenger may have shortened the anticipated exchange by going directly to the key news (v. 23).</p>",
        "23": "<p>The messenger&rsquo;s report to David: the enemy came out against them in the open field (<em>ki gavru aleinu ha-anashim vayetz&rsquo;u eleinu ha-sadeh</em>), but Israel pushed them back to the city gate (<em>vayihyu-aleinu ad-petach ha-sha&rsquo;ar</em>). The tactical narrative explains how the forces came to be close enough to the wall to suffer archery fire. The messenger does not wait for David&rsquo;s anger to develop before delivering the Uriah news (v. 24).</p>",
        "24": "<p>The archers shot at your servants from the wall (<em>vayoru ha-moreh el-avadekha me-al ha-chomah</em>), and some of the king&rsquo;s men died (<em>vayamutu mi-avdei ha-melekh</em>), and your servant Uriah the Hittite is dead too (<em>vegam Uriyah ha-Chitti met</em>). Again the <em>gam</em> (also/too) places Uriah among the others who died, normalizing a murder. The messenger faithfully delivers the information exactly as Joab instructed, ending with Uriah&rsquo;s death as the key fact.</p>",
        "25": "<p>David&rsquo;s response to the messenger: <em>ko-tomar el Yo&rsquo;av al-yera&rsquo; bedavrekhа kaze vegam-zeh vegam-zeh tokhal ha-cherev chazzeq milchamtekha el-ha-ir uharesah vechazeqehu</em> (&ldquo;Tell Joab: Do not let this distress you &mdash; the sword is no respecter of persons. Press the attack against the city and take it.&rdquo;). The phrase <em>lo-tova ha-cherev</em> (the sword consumes impartially/does not pick its victims) is a military aphorism &mdash; David normalizes the deaths, including Uriah&rsquo;s, as the cost of war. The consolation is hollow: David is consoling Joab for doing exactly what David requested. The phrase <em>vegam-zeh vegam-zeh</em> (&ldquo;this one and that one&rdquo;) makes all deaths equivalent and all deaths acceptable.</p>",
        "26": "<p>When Uriah&rsquo;s wife (<em>eshet Uriyah</em>) heard that her husband was dead, she mourned for him (<em>vattispod al-ba&rsquo;alah</em>). She is referred to as &ldquo;Uriah&rsquo;s wife&rdquo; even in her widowhood &mdash; the narrative maintains her identity in relation to her husband through the mourning period. The mourning (<em>saphad</em>) is a standard death ritual. The period of mourning is unspecified but conventional (cf. Gen 27:41: Isaac&rsquo;s death mourning period; Num 20:29: thirty days for Aaron). David waits out the mourning period before acting.</p>",
        "27": "<p><em>Vaya&rsquo;avor ha-ebel vayishlach David vaya&rsquo;asepehah el-beito vattehi-lo le-ishshah vateled-lo ben</em> (&ldquo;when the mourning period was over, David sent for her and brought her to his palace. She became his wife and bore him a son&rdquo;). The cover-up appears complete: a respectable interval observed, a formal marriage, a child born in wedlock. But the final clause demolishes the appearance: <em>vayera&rsquo; ha-davar asher asah David be-einei YHWH</em> (&ldquo;but the thing David had done was evil in the LORD&rsquo;s sight&rdquo;). The verdict formula <em>be-einei YHWH</em> (in the eyes/sight of YHWH) is the standard Deuteronomistic evaluative judgment used throughout Kings and Samuel. For the first time in the David narrative, that judgment is categorically negative: <em>ra&rsquo;</em> (evil). YHWH&rsquo;s sight penetrates what human observation cannot; the chapter that David has choreographed to conceal his sin concludes with YHWH seeing it all.</p>",
    },
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-original", "2samuel")
    merged = merge_comm(existing, SAMUEL2)
    save_comm("mkt-original", "2samuel", merged)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
